HR Notes Feature — Frontend Integration Guide
Base URL
https://api.casi360.com/api/v1

Endpoints
Method	Endpoint	Auth	Description
GET	/hr/notes	Any authenticated	List notes (paginated)
GET	/hr/notes/{id}	Any authenticated	Get single note
POST	/hr/notes	Admin/Manager only	Create note
PATCH	/hr/notes/{id}	Admin/Manager only	Update note
DELETE	/hr/notes/{id}	Admin/Manager only	Delete note
GET /hr/notes — Query Parameters
Param	Type	Default	Description
search	string	—	Searches title and content
employee_id	string (UUID)	—	Filter by employee
type	string	—	general, performance, disciplinary, commendation, medical, training
priority	string	—	low, medium, high
sort_by	string	created_at	Options: title, type, priority, created_at, updated_at
sort_dir	string	desc	asc or desc
per_page	int	15	Max 100
page	int	1	Page number
List Response Shape (GET /hr/notes)
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Success",
  "data": {
    "notes": [
      {
        "id": "uuid",
        "employee_id": "uuid",
        "employee": {
          "id": "uuid",
          "name": "Adaeze Obi"
        },
        "title": "Performance Review Q1",
        "content": "Full note body text...",
        "type": "performance",
        "priority": "high",
        "created_by": "uuid",
        "created_by_name": "Daniel Okonkwo",
        "created_at": "2026-01-15T10:00:00.000000Z",
        "updated_at": "2026-01-15T10:00:00.000000Z"
      }
    ],
    "meta": {
      "current_page": 1,
      "last_page": 3,
      "per_page": 15,
      "total": 42,
      "from": 1,
      "to": 15
    }
  }
}

Single Note Response (GET /hr/notes/{id})
Same note object, wrapped as:
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Success",
  "data": {
    "note": { ... }
  }
}


Create Note (POST /hr/notes)
Request body:{
  "employee_id": "uuid",
  "title": "Performance Review Q1",
  "content": "Full note body text",
  "type": "performance",
  "priority": "high"
}

Field	Type	Required	Notes
employee_id	UUID string	yes	Must be a valid employee UUID
title	string	yes	Max 255 chars
content	string	yes	Max 10,000 chars
type	string	no	Default: general. Options: general, performance, disciplinary, commendation, medical, training
priority	string	no	Default: medium. Options: low, medium, high
created_by is set automatically from the authenticated user — do not send it.

Success response (201):
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Note created successfully",
  "data": {
    "note": { ... }
  }
}



Update Note (PATCH /hr/notes/{id})
Send only the fields you want to change. All fields are optional.
{
  "title": "Updated title",
  "priority": "low"
}

Success response (200):
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Note updated successfully",
  "data": {
    "note": { ... }
  }
}


Delete Note (DELETE /hr/notes/{id})
No request body needed. This is a hard delete (note is permanently removed).

Success response (200):
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Note deleted successfully",
  "data": null
}


Validation Errors (422)

{
  "success": false,
  "message": "The employee id field is required.",
  "errors": {
    "employee_id": ["The employee id field is required."],
    "title": ["The title field is required."]
  }
}


Employee Dropdown
To populate the employee selector in the create/edit modal, use the existing endpoint:
GET /hr/employees?per_page=0
This returns all employees (no pagination). Use id as the value and name as the label.

Enums for Dropdowns
Type options:
const NOTE_TYPES = ['general', 'performance', 'disciplinary', 'commendation', 'medical', 'training'] as const;

Priority options:
const NOTE_PRIORITIES = ['low', 'medium', 'high'] as const;

Role-Based UI
Role	Can view	Can create/edit/delete
super_admin	Yes	Yes
admin	Yes	Yes
manager	Yes	Yes
staff	Yes	No — hide create/edit/delete buttons
Key Notes for Frontend
The data key in list responses uses notes (not data or items)
employee is a nested object { id, name }, not a flat string
created_by_name is a resolved string (display-only), created_by is the UUID
Pagination meta includes from and to for showing "Showing 1–15 of 42"
Default sort is created_at descending (newest first)
The API follows the same auth pattern as all other HR endpoints (Sanctum cookie-based)


================================================================================
Dynamic Permissions System — Frontend Integration Guide
================================================================================

Overview
--------
The backend now has a dynamic permissions system. Instead of hardcoded role checks,
every feature/action is controlled by a database-driven permission that the super admin
can toggle on/off per role from a settings page.

Super admin always has full access (hardcoded bypass — cannot be locked out).


How It Works
------------
1. User logs in
2. Frontend calls GET /api/v1/auth/permissions
3. Backend returns a flat map of permission keys → true/false
4. Frontend stores this map (e.g. in context/store)
5. Use the map to show/hide UI elements across the entire app


GET /api/v1/auth/permissions — User's Permission Map
-----------------------------------------------------
Any authenticated user can call this. Returns their resolved permissions.

Response (200):
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Success",
  "data": {
    "permissions": {
      "auth.users.view": true,
      "auth.users.create": true,
      "auth.users.edit": true,
      "auth.users.delete": true,
      "auth.users.manage_roles": true,
      "auth.users.manage_status": true,
      "hr.departments.view": true,
      "hr.departments.create": true,
      "hr.departments.edit": true,
      "hr.departments.delete": true,
      "hr.designations.view": true,
      "hr.designations.create": true,
      "hr.designations.edit": true,
      "hr.designations.delete": true,
      "hr.employees.view": true,
      "hr.employees.create": true,
      "hr.employees.edit": true,
      "hr.employees.delete": true,
      "hr.employees.manage_status": true,
      "hr.notes.view": true,
      "hr.notes.create": true,
      "hr.notes.edit": true,
      "hr.notes.delete": true
    }
  }
}

For super_admin: all permissions are always true.
For other roles: values reflect what the super admin has configured.


Permission Key Format
---------------------
Pattern: module.feature.action

Examples:
  hr.notes.view         → Can see the notes list and details
  hr.notes.create       → Can create new notes
  hr.notes.edit         → Can edit existing notes
  hr.notes.delete       → Can delete notes
  hr.departments.view   → Can see departments
  hr.employees.create   → Can create employees
  auth.users.view       → Can see user management


Frontend Usage Pattern
----------------------
1. Fetch permissions once after login (or from session):

   const res = await api.get('/auth/permissions');
   const permissions = res.data.data.permissions;

2. Store in your auth context/store alongside the user object.

3. Use throughout the app:

   // Show/hide a button
   {permissions['hr.notes.create'] && <Button>Add Note</Button>}

   // Show/hide a menu item
   {permissions['auth.users.view'] && <MenuItem>User Management</MenuItem>}

   // Show/hide edit/delete actions in a table row
   {permissions['hr.notes.edit'] && <EditButton />}
   {permissions['hr.notes.delete'] && <DeleteButton />}

   // Hide entire page/section
   {permissions['hr.departments.view'] && <DepartmentsPage />}

4. Helper function (recommended):

   function can(permission: string): boolean {
     // Super admin check (if you store user role locally)
     if (user.role === 'super_admin') return true;
     return permissions[permission] === true;
   }

   // Usage:
   {can('hr.notes.create') && <Button>Add Note</Button>}


When to Refresh Permissions
---------------------------
- After login (initial fetch)
- After the user's session is restored (page reload)
- You do NOT need to poll — permissions rarely change during a session
- If the super admin changes permissions, affected users will see changes on next login/refresh


403 Error Handling
------------------
If a user somehow calls an endpoint they don't have permission for (e.g. button shown
due to stale permissions), the backend returns:

{
  "success": false,
  "message": "You do not have permission to perform this action."
}

Status: 403

Handle this gracefully — show a toast/alert and optionally re-fetch permissions.


Default Permissions by Role
---------------------------
These are the initial defaults. Super admin can change any of them.

Role        | auth.users.* | hr.*.view | hr.*.create/edit/delete
------------|-------------|-----------|------------------------
super_admin | Always all  | Always all| Always all (hardcoded)
admin       | All true    | All true  | All true
manager     | All false   | All true  | All true
staff       | All false   | All true  | All false


================================================================================
Super Admin Settings Page — Permissions Management
================================================================================

This section is for building the permissions settings page (super_admin only).


GET /api/v1/settings/permissions — Full Permission Matrix
----------------------------------------------------------
Super admin only. Returns all permissions with role mappings.

Response (200):
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Success",
  "data": {
    "permissions": [
      {
        "id": "uuid",
        "module": "hr",
        "feature": "notes",
        "action": "create",
        "key": "hr.notes.create",
        "description": "Create employee notes",
        "roles": {
          "admin": true,
          "manager": true,
          "staff": false
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "uuid",
        "module": "hr",
        "feature": "notes",
        "action": "view",
        "key": "hr.notes.view",
        "description": "View employee notes",
        "roles": {
          "admin": true,
          "manager": true,
          "staff": true
        }
      }
    ],
    "roles": ["admin", "manager", "staff"]
  }
}

Note: super_admin is NOT in the roles list — they always have full access.


PATCH /api/v1/settings/permissions/{id} — Toggle Single Permission
------------------------------------------------------------------
Super admin only. Toggle one role's access to one permission.

Request body:
{
  "role": "staff",
  "allowed": true
}

Fields:
  role      string   required   One of: admin, manager, staff
  allowed   boolean  required   true = grant, false = revoke

Response (200):
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Permission updated successfully",
  "data": {
    "role_permission": {
      "id": "uuid",
      "role": "staff",
      "permission_key": "hr.notes.create",
      "allowed": true
    }
  }
}


PATCH /api/v1/settings/permissions/bulk — Bulk Update Permissions
-----------------------------------------------------------------
Super admin only. Update multiple permissions at once (e.g. "Save All" button).

Request body:
{
  "permissions": [
    { "permission_id": "uuid-1", "role": "staff", "allowed": true },
    { "permission_id": "uuid-2", "role": "staff", "allowed": false },
    { "permission_id": "uuid-3", "role": "manager", "allowed": false }
  ]
}

Fields per item:
  permission_id   string (UUID)   required   The permission's UUID
  role            string          required   One of: admin, manager, staff
  allowed         boolean         required   true = grant, false = revoke

Response (200):
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Permissions updated successfully",
  "data": {
    "updated": 3
  }
}


Settings Page UI Suggestion
---------------------------
Build a matrix/table like this:

Permission              | Admin | Manager | Staff
------------------------|-------|---------|------
View Users              |  [x]  |  [ ]    |  [ ]
Create Users            |  [x]  |  [ ]    |  [ ]
View Departments        |  [x]  |  [x]    |  [x]
Create Departments      |  [x]  |  [x]    |  [ ]
Edit Departments        |  [x]  |  [x]    |  [ ]
Delete Departments      |  [x]  |  [x]    |  [ ]
View Notes              |  [x]  |  [x]    |  [x]
Create Notes            |  [x]  |  [x]    |  [ ]
...

Each checkbox toggles via PATCH /settings/permissions/{id}.
Or collect all changes and send via PATCH /settings/permissions/bulk on "Save".

Group rows by module (Auth, HR, Procurement, etc.) for clarity.
The "description" field from the API can be used as the display label.
The "module" and "feature" fields can be used for grouping/sectioning.

Super admin row is NOT shown — they always have everything.


Endpoints Summary
-----------------
Method  Endpoint                            Access          Description
GET     /api/v1/auth/permissions            Any auth user   Current user's permission map
GET     /api/v1/settings/permissions        Super admin     Full matrix for settings page
PATCH   /api/v1/settings/permissions/{id}   Super admin     Toggle one permission
PATCH   /api/v1/settings/permissions/bulk   Super admin     Bulk toggle permissions


Key Notes for Frontend
----------------------
- Call GET /auth/permissions after every login and store the result
- Use the permission map to show/hide ALL UI elements (buttons, menus, pages)
- The backend also enforces permissions — frontend hiding is for UX, not security
- New permissions are automatically added when new backend modules are deployed
- After re-fetching permissions, the UI should reactively update
- super_admin always gets { key: true } for every permission — no special frontend logic needed
- The settings page is only accessible to super_admin users


SERVER IP:
cd /home/casi360/public_html && git pull origin main && npm install && npm run build && pm2 restart casi360


================================================================================
Purchase Request — Approval Workflow Specification
================================================================================

Overview & Recommendation
--------------------------
The physical PR form has 4 sign-off columns: Requester, Budget Holder, Finance,
and Logistics. The digital equivalent should mirror this exactly but with one key
improvement: all approving units see the PR simultaneously (full transparency),
while only the unit whose stage is currently "active" can take an action.

This avoids the "queue and wait" problem where Finance doesn't even see the PR
until the Budget Holder acts — instead, everyone sees everything always, but the
action buttons are unlocked only when it is your turn.

There are 3 approval STAGES (matching the physical form, minus the Requester who
is the submitter — not an approver):

  Stage 1 — Budget Holder    (validates budget availability)
  Stage 2 — Finance          (financial approval; can finalize or forward)
  Stage 3 — Operations       (final logistics sign-off; only if Finance forwards)

Finance is special: they can either APPROVE FINAL (closes the chain) or
FORWARD TO OPERATIONS (activates Stage 3 before the PR is fully approved).


================================================================================
1. DATABASE — NEW TABLE: requisition_approvals
================================================================================

Create one row per stage per requisition when a PR is submitted.

  Column          Type                  Notes
  ------          ----                  -----
  id              UUID PK
  requisition_id  UUID FK               → requisitions.id, CASCADE DELETE
  stage           ENUM                  'budget_holder' | 'finance' | 'operations'
  stage_order     TINYINT               1, 2, 3 — controls display order
  stage_label     VARCHAR(50)           "Budget Holder", "Finance", "Operations"
  status          ENUM                  see Status Enum below
  actor_id        UUID NULL FK          → users.id — who took the action
  actor_name      VARCHAR NULL          resolved name (snapshot)
  actor_position  VARCHAR NULL          resolved position/designation (snapshot)
  comments        TEXT NULL             required on reject/revision, optional otherwise
  decided_at      TIMESTAMP NULL        when the action was taken
  created_at      TIMESTAMP
  updated_at      TIMESTAMP

Status Enum for each stage row:
  waiting     — Not yet this stage's turn (locked)
  pending     — This stage is now active; awaiting action
  approved    — Approved by this stage
  forwarded   — Finance approved and forwarded to Operations (Finance-only status)
  rejected    — Rejected at this stage (PR goes to rejected)
  revision    — Sent back for revision (PR goes to revision)
  skipped     — Operations stage was skipped (Finance approved final)


================================================================================
2. STAGE CREATION — WHEN A PR IS SUBMITTED
================================================================================

When POST /procurement/requisitions/{id}/submit is called:

1. Create 3 rows in requisition_approvals:
   - Stage 1 (budget_holder):  status = 'pending'    ← active immediately
   - Stage 2 (finance):        status = 'waiting'
   - Stage 3 (operations):     status = 'waiting'

2. Update requisition status = 'pending_approval'

3. (Optional but recommended) Fire an in-app notification or email to all users
   with the `procurement.approvals.budget_holder` permission that a PR needs review.

Do NOT create approval rows when the PR is first created (draft) — only on submit.
If a PR is sent back for revision and re-submitted, RESET the approval chain:
delete the old approval rows and create fresh ones.


================================================================================
3. STAGE TRANSITION RULES
================================================================================

When PATCH /procurement/requisitions/{id}/approval is called:

Action: "approve"
  - If active stage = budget_holder:
      → Set stage 1 status = 'approved', decided_at = now, actor = auth user
      → Set stage 2 status = 'pending'
      → Notify Finance users

  - If active stage = finance AND action = "approve" (final):
      → Set stage 2 status = 'approved', decided_at = now, actor = auth user
      → Set stage 3 status = 'skipped'
      → Update requisition status = 'approved'
      → Notify requester

  - If active stage = operations:
      → Set stage 3 status = 'approved', decided_at = now, actor = auth user
      → Update requisition status = 'approved'
      → Notify requester

Action: "forward"  (Finance ONLY — activates Operations stage)
  - Only valid when active stage = finance
      → Set stage 2 status = 'forwarded', decided_at = now, actor = auth user
      → Set stage 3 status = 'pending'
      → Notify Operations users
      → Requisition status remains 'pending_approval'

Action: "reject"
  - Set current stage status = 'rejected', decided_at = now, actor = auth user
  - Set all remaining 'pending'/'waiting' stages to 'waiting' (untouch them)
  - Update requisition status = 'rejected'
  - Notify requester

Action: "revision"
  - Set current stage status = 'revision', decided_at = now, actor = auth user
  - Set all remaining 'pending'/'waiting' stages to 'waiting'
  - Update requisition status = 'revision'
  - Notify requester (they can now edit and re-submit)

VALIDATION — Server must enforce who can call this:
  - Budget Holder action: user must have 'procurement.approvals.budget_holder' permission
  - Finance action: user must have 'procurement.approvals.finance' permission
  - Operations action: user must have 'procurement.approvals.operations' permission
  - Return 403 if user tries to act on a stage they don't own
  - Return 422 if the stage is not currently 'pending' (e.g., trying to approve
    a stage that is still 'waiting' or already 'approved')


================================================================================
4. UPDATED PROCESS APPROVAL ENDPOINT
================================================================================

PATCH /procurement/requisitions/{id}/approval

Request body:
{
  "action":   "approve | reject | revision | forward",
  "comments": "string (required for reject and revision, optional for others)"
}

Validation:
  action      required, in:approve,reject,revision,forward
  comments    required_if:action,reject | required_if:action,revision | max:1000

Success response (200):
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Purchase request approved by Budget Holder",
  "data": {
    "requisition": {
      ...full requisition object with approval_chain...
    }
  }
}

Error — wrong stage / not your turn (403):
{
  "success": false,
  "message": "You are not authorised to approve at the current stage."
}

Error — stage not active (422):
{
  "success": false,
  "message": "This approval stage is not currently awaiting action."
}


================================================================================
5. APPROVAL CHAIN — RESPONSE SHAPE
================================================================================

Include this in EVERY requisition response (list items, single GET, and after
any approval action). The frontend uses this to render the visual chain.

"approval_chain": [
  {
    "stage":          "budget_holder",
    "stage_label":    "Budget Holder",
    "stage_order":    1,
    "status":         "approved",
    "actor_id":       "uuid",
    "actor_name":     "Amina Hassan",
    "actor_position": "Programme Manager",
    "comments":       null,
    "decided_at":     "2026-04-21T10:30:00.000000Z"
  },
  {
    "stage":          "finance",
    "stage_label":    "Finance",
    "stage_order":    2,
    "status":         "pending",
    "actor_id":       null,
    "actor_name":     null,
    "actor_position": null,
    "comments":       null,
    "decided_at":     null
  },
  {
    "stage":          "operations",
    "stage_label":    "Operations",
    "stage_order":    3,
    "status":         "waiting",
    "actor_id":       null,
    "actor_name":     null,
    "actor_position": null,
    "comments":       null,
    "decided_at":     null
  }
],
"active_stage": "finance",
"approval_progress": {
  "completed": 1,
  "total": 3
}

active_stage values: "budget_holder" | "finance" | "operations" | null (if approved/rejected)

NOTE: For list endpoints, including full approval_chain per row may be heavy.
Minimum required on list rows: active_stage + approval_progress + approval_chain (status only).
Full actor details (name, comments, decided_at) are needed in the detail view.


================================================================================
6. UPDATED PENDING APPROVALS ENDPOINT
================================================================================

The existing GET /procurement/pending-approvals endpoint must be enhanced.
It currently returns { purchase_orders, requisitions } for the current user.

New behaviour: Return ALL submitted/pending_approval requisitions, grouped/filtered
by the authenticated user's approval role. The frontend for each module queries
this same endpoint but the backend filters based on who is calling:

  - User with 'budget_holder' permission → sees PRs where Stage 1 is 'pending'
  - User with 'finance' permission → sees PRs where Stage 2 is 'pending'
  - User with 'operations' permission → sees PRs where Stage 3 is 'pending'
  - User with admin/super_admin → sees ALL pending PRs at any stage

ADDITIONALLY: All three modules want to show the full pipeline for transparency
(not just "my turn" items). So the endpoint should support a query parameter:

GET /procurement/pending-approvals?scope=mine      ← only items awaiting MY action
GET /procurement/pending-approvals?scope=all       ← all in-flight PRs (any stage)
GET /procurement/pending-approvals                 ← defaults to 'mine'

Each item in the response must include the approval_chain array so the frontend
can display who has approved and who hasn't without a second API call.

Response shape:
{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "purchase_orders": [ ...PO items with approval_progress... ],
    "requisitions": [
      {
        "id":                 "uuid",
        "requisition_number": "PR-2026-0042",
        "title":              "Office Supplies Q2",
        "requested_by_name":  "Daniel Ishaku",
        "department":         "Administration",
        "project_code":       "CAID-001",
        "donor":              "USAID",
        "estimated_cost":     185000.00,
        "priority":           "medium",
        "status":             "pending_approval",
        "needed_by":          "2026-05-10",
        "submitted_at":       "2026-04-21T09:15:00.000000Z",
        "active_stage":       "finance",
        "approval_progress":  { "completed": 1, "total": 3 },
        "approval_chain": [
          { "stage": "budget_holder", "stage_label": "Budget Holder", "stage_order": 1, "status": "approved", "actor_name": "Amina Hassan", "decided_at": "2026-04-21T10:30:00Z" },
          { "stage": "finance",       "stage_label": "Finance",       "stage_order": 2, "status": "pending",  "actor_name": null, "decided_at": null },
          { "stage": "operations",    "stage_label": "Operations",    "stage_order": 3, "status": "waiting",  "actor_name": null, "decided_at": null }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}


