================================================================================
8. FRONTEND — HOW EACH MODULE'S APPROVALS PAGE BEHAVES
================================================================================

All three approval pages (Procurement, Finance, Operations) call the SAME endpoint:
  GET /procurement/pending-approvals

The difference is which users access which page, and what action buttons they see.

--- Procurement > Pending Approvals ---
  - Audience: Budget Holders (managers, department heads, procurement team)
  - Default scope: 'mine' — shows PRs where Stage 1 is currently 'pending'
  - Can toggle to 'all' to see all in-flight PRs
  - Action buttons: Approve | Reject | Request Revision (for Stage 1 items only)
  - Shows approval_chain strip on each row so they can see overall progress
  - Already exists — needs to be updated to use new response shape

--- Finance > Approvals ---
  - Audience: Finance team
  - Default scope: 'mine' — shows PRs where Stage 2 is currently 'pending'
  - Action buttons: Approve (Final) | Forward to Operations | Reject | Request Revision
  - "Forward to Operations" sends action = "forward" and activates Stage 3
  - Shows budget context: project, budget line, available budget before/after
  - Currently demo-backed — replace with live API call to pending-approvals endpoint

--- Operations > Approvals (new page to create) ---
  - Audience: Operations/Logistics team
  - Default scope: 'mine' — shows PRs where Stage 3 is currently 'pending'
  - PRs only appear here if Finance previously clicked "Forward to Operations"
  - Action buttons: Approve | Reject | Request Revision (for Stage 3 items only)
  - This module/page does not yet exist on the frontend — will be built once backend is ready

UNIVERSAL RULE (backend enforced, frontend reflects):
  If a user tries to call processApproval on a PR that is not in their active stage,
  the backend returns 403. The frontend hides irrelevant action buttons using the
  active_stage field from the response, so users only see buttons when it's their turn.


================================================================================
9. PERMISSIONS — NEW APPROVAL PERMISSION KEYS
================================================================================

Add these to the dynamic permissions system:

Key                                    Description
---                                    -----------
procurement.approvals.view             Can see the Approvals page
procurement.approvals.budget_holder    Can act as Budget Holder (Stage 1)
procurement.approvals.finance          Can act as Finance approver (Stage 2)
procurement.approvals.operations       Can act as Operations approver (Stage 3)

Suggested defaults:

Role          | view  | budget_holder | finance | operations
--------------|-------|---------------|---------|------------
super_admin   | true  | true          | true    | true   (hardcoded)
admin         | true  | true          | true    | true
manager       | true  | true          | false   | false
staff         | true  | false         | false   | false

IMPORTANT: A user should normally have only ONE of the three action permissions.
Giving someone both budget_holder AND finance means they could approve both stages
themselves — the system allows it technically but it defeats the purpose.
Training/role assignment should enforce separation.


================================================================================
10. DESIGN NOTES & RECOMMENDATIONS
================================================================================

1. SNAPSHOT actor details at decision time.
   Store actor_name and actor_position in the approval row at the time of action.
   Do NOT rely on joining to users table at query time — names and positions can change.

2. RESET the approval chain on re-submission.
   When a PR in 'revision' status is re-submitted, delete the old approval rows
   and create fresh ones. This gives a clean slate for the new review cycle.
   (Consider keeping old chains in an audit log table if you want full history.)

3. `comments` on each stage row replaces the "Comments / Special" column from
   the physical form. Budget Holder and Finance comments are both stored and
   visible in the chain display — not just the most recent.

4. `actor_position` captures the signer's formal position (e.g. "Finance Officer",
   "Programme Manager") — the digital equivalent of the "Position" row in the
   physical form. Pull this from user.designation or user.position at action time.

5. For Operations: since Finance decides whether to forward, the Operations stage
   may never be created for some PRs. Use `status = 'skipped'` (already in the chain
   from creation) so the frontend can always show all 3 stages and display
   "N/A" or "Skipped" for Operations when Finance approved final.

6. NOTIFICATIONS (recommended next step):
   - When PR is submitted → notify Budget Holders in the PR's department
   - When Stage 1 approved → notify Finance team
   - When Stage 2 forwarded → notify Operations team
   - When approved/rejected → notify the original requester

7. EMAIL AUDIT TRAIL:
   Each approval action should ideally trigger an email to all parties
   showing the current state of the chain. This gives a paper trail that mirrors
   what staff were used to with physical forms.


================================================================================
11. APPROVAL WORKFLOW QUICK REFERENCE
================================================================================

  PR Submitted
       │
       ▼
  Stage 1: BUDGET HOLDER (pending)
       │
       ├── approve → Stage 2: FINANCE (pending)
       │                  │
       │                  ├── approve (final) → Stage 3: skipped → PR = approved
       │                  │
       │                  ├── forward to ops → Stage 3: OPERATIONS (pending)
       │                  │                         │
       │                  │                         └── approve → PR = approved
       │                  │                         └── reject  → PR = rejected
       │                  │                         └── revision → PR = revision
       │                  │
       │                  ├── reject   → PR = rejected
       │                  └── revision → PR = revision
       │
       ├── reject   → PR = rejected
       └── revision → PR = revision

  PR = revision → requester edits → re-submits → Stage 1 resets to pending

================================================================================
