================================================================================
Purchase Request Module — Backend Engineering Specification
================================================================================

Overview
--------
The Purchase Request (PR / Requisition) module is used across THREE sections of the
app: Procurement, HR, and Finance. All three use the EXACT same backend endpoints
and data structure — the module prefix in the UI is cosmetic only. Do NOT create
separate tables or endpoints per module. One unified requisitions table serves all.

The frontend submits `requested_by` (UUID of the logged-in user) automatically — no
employee picker. The requester is always the authenticated user.

Base URL
--------
https://api.casi360.com/api/v1


================================================================================
1. PURCHASE REQUISITIONS — CRUD ENDPOINTS
================================================================================

Method   Endpoint                                      Description
------   --------                                      -----------
GET      /procurement/requisitions                     List (paginated + filtered)
GET      /procurement/requisitions/{id}                Get single PR
POST     /procurement/requisitions                     Create new PR
PATCH    /procurement/requisitions/{id}                Update PR (draft/revision only)
DELETE   /procurement/requisitions/{id}                Cancel PR (soft delete / set status=cancelled)
POST     /procurement/requisitions/{id}/submit         Submit PR for approval
GET      /procurement/requisitions/{id}/approval-status  Get current approval chain status
PATCH    /procurement/requisitions/{id}/approval       Process an approval decision


================================================================================
2. CREATE / UPDATE — REQUEST BODY
================================================================================

POST /procurement/requisitions
PATCH /procurement/requisitions/{id}

All fields are optional on PATCH (send only what changed).

{
  "title":               "string (required on create, max 255)",
  "date":                "2026-04-21 (ISO date string, defaults to today)",
  "department_id":       "uuid — must be a valid department",
  "requested_by":        "uuid — set automatically from auth user on frontend; backend should also derive this from session and ignore/override any value sent",
  "delivery_location":   "string (max 255)",
  "needed_by":           "2026-05-10 (ISO date string — the delivery/required date)",
  "purchase_scenario":   "one of: Direct Purchase | Competitive Bidding | Framework Agreement | Emergency Purchase | Sole Source",
  "logistics_involved":  "Yes | No",
  "boq":                 "Yes | No",
  "project_code":        "string — the project code (e.g. 'CAID-001'), not the project UUID",
  "donor":               "string — donor name as free text (resolved from project's donors list on frontend)",
  "currency":            "NGN | USD | EUR (default: NGN)",
  "exchange_rate":       "number — required if currency != NGN, rate to NGN (e.g. 1550.00)",
  "priority":            "low | medium | high | urgent (default: medium)",
  "justification":       "text — reason for the purchase request",
  "notes":               "text — additional notes or special instructions",
  "items": [
    {
      "description":          "string (required) — item description",
      "unit":                 "string — unit of measure (e.g. Pcs, Litres, Kg)",
      "quantity":             "number (default: 1)",
      "estimated_unit_cost":  "number (decimal, e.g. 45000.00)",
      "project_code":         "string — may differ per line item; defaults to the header project_code",
      "budget_line":          "string — the description field from the project's budget-lines API",
      "inventory_item_id":    "uuid | null — optional link to an inventory item"
    }
  ]
}

IMPORTANT NOTES:
- `requested_by` must always be derived from the authenticated session server-side.
  Even though the frontend sends it, the backend should enforce this and not allow
  a user to submit a PR on behalf of someone else.
- `items` that have no `description` are filtered out by the frontend before sending —
  but validate server-side and skip/reject blank items.
- `estimated_cost` (the PR total) should be COMPUTED by the backend as:
  SUM(quantity * estimated_unit_cost) across all items. Do not accept it as input.
- `exchange_rate` is only relevant when `currency != NGN`. When currency is NGN,
  ignore it. When currency is USD or EUR, store the exchange rate so the Naira
  equivalent can be displayed/reported.
- On PATCH, if `items` is sent, REPLACE the full items array (not merge).
  The frontend always sends the full items list on edit.


================================================================================
3. LIST RESPONSE — GET /procurement/requisitions
================================================================================

Query Parameters:

Param           Type      Default       Description
-----           ----      -------       -----------
search          string    —             Search title, requisition_number, requested_by_name
status          string    —             Filter by status (see status enum below)
priority        string    —             Filter by priority: low | medium | high | urgent
page            int       1             Page number
per_page        int       15            Results per page (max 100)
sort_by         string    created_at    Options: created_at, needed_by, estimated_cost, priority, status
sort_dir        string    desc          asc | desc

Response Shape (200):

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Success",
  "data": {
    "requisitions": [
      {
        "id":                   "uuid",
        "requisition_number":   "PR-2026-0042",
        "title":                "Office Supplies Q2",
        "date":                 "2026-04-21",
        "department_id":        "uuid",
        "department":           "Administration",
        "requested_by":         "uuid",
        "requested_by_name":    "Daniel Ishaku",
        "project_code":         "CAID-001",
        "donor":                "USAID",
        "currency":             "NGN",
        "exchange_rate":        null,
        "estimated_cost":       185000.00,
        "item_count":           4,
        "priority":             "medium",
        "status":               "draft",
        "needed_by":            "2026-05-10",
        "purchase_scenario":    "Direct Purchase",
        "logistics_involved":   "No",
        "boq":                  "No",
        "purchase_order_number": null,
        "created_at":           "2026-04-21T09:15:00.000000Z",
        "updated_at":           "2026-04-21T09:15:00.000000Z"
      }
    ],
    "meta": {
      "current_page": 1,
      "last_page": 4,
      "per_page": 15,
      "total": 58,
      "from": 1,
      "to": 15
    }
  }
}

Fields the frontend uses from each list item:
  id, requisition_number, title, requested_by_name, department, estimated_cost,
  item_count, priority, status, needed_by, purchase_order_number, created_at

`department` must be the resolved name string, not just department_id.
`requested_by_name` must be the resolved full name, not just the UUID.
`estimated_cost` must be the computed sum from items.
`item_count` is the count of line items on this PR.
`purchase_order_number` is null until a PO is raised from this PR.


================================================================================
4. SINGLE PR RESPONSE — GET /procurement/requisitions/{id}
================================================================================

This endpoint is used for the Edit form (pre-populates all fields).
Must return the FULL record including the complete items array.

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Success",
  "data": {
    "requisition": {
      "id":                   "uuid",
      "requisition_number":   "PR-2026-0042",
      "title":                "Office Supplies Q2",
      "date":                 "2026-04-21",
      "department_id":        "uuid",
      "department":           "Administration",
      "requested_by":         "uuid",
      "requested_by_name":    "Daniel Ishaku",
      "delivery_location":    "Head Office, Abuja",
      "needed_by":            "2026-05-10",
      "purchase_scenario":    "Direct Purchase",
      "logistics_involved":   "No",
      "boq":                  "No",
      "project_code":         "CAID-001",
      "donor":                "USAID",
      "currency":             "NGN",
      "exchange_rate":        null,
      "priority":             "medium",
      "status":               "draft",
      "justification":        "Required for Q2 operations...",
      "notes":                "Urgent — needed before end of April",
      "estimated_cost":       185000.00,
      "item_count":           4,
      "purchase_order_number": null,
      "created_at":           "2026-04-21T09:15:00.000000Z",
      "updated_at":           "2026-04-21T09:15:00.000000Z",
      "items": [
        {
          "id":                    "uuid",
          "description":           "A4 Printer Paper",
          "unit":                  "Ream",
          "quantity":              10,
          "estimated_unit_cost":   4500.00,
          "project_code":          "CAID-001",
          "budget_line":           "Community Volunteer Training",
          "inventory_item_id":     null
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}

NOTE: The frontend edit form expects the items array at `pr.items` (not nested deeper).
The frontend also looks for: `res?.data?.requisition || res?.data?.purchase_request || res?.data`
— so wrapping as `data.requisition` is the recommended and expected shape.


================================================================================
5. STATUS ENUM & WORKFLOW
================================================================================

Valid status values (used in list filter and displayed in UI):

  draft             — Initial state when created
  submitted         — Submitted for review (via POST .../submit)
  pending_approval  — In approval chain
  approved          — Fully approved
  rejected          — Rejected by approver
  revision          — Sent back for revision (user can edit and re-submit)
  fulfilled         — PR has been fulfilled (linked PO delivered)
  cancelled         — Cancelled / soft-deleted

State transition rules:
  draft       → submitted       (via POST /submit)
  submitted   → pending_approval, approved, rejected, revision  (via approval endpoints)
  revision    → submitted       (user edits and re-submits)
  approved    → fulfilled       (when linked PO is received)
  any         → cancelled       (via DELETE endpoint)

The frontend only allows EDIT on status = 'draft' or 'revision'.
The DELETE button is always visible (to authorised users) and sets status = 'cancelled'.
The frontend label for DELETE is "Cancel Purchase Request" — this is a soft cancel, NOT a hard delete.


================================================================================
6. SUBMIT ENDPOINT
================================================================================

POST /procurement/requisitions/{id}/submit

No request body needed. Transitions status from 'draft' or 'revision' → 'submitted'.
Returns the updated requisition object.

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Purchase request submitted successfully",
  "data": {
    "requisition": { ...full requisition object... }
  }
}


================================================================================
7. APPROVAL ENDPOINTS
================================================================================

GET /procurement/requisitions/{id}/approval-status

Returns the current approval chain for this PR.

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Success",
  "data": {
    "approvals": [
      {
        "id":            "uuid",
        "level":         1,
        "approver_id":   "uuid",
        "approver_name": "Amina Hassan",
        "status":        "pending | approved | rejected",
        "comments":      null,
        "decided_at":    null
      }
    ],
    "overall_status": "pending_approval"
  }
}

PATCH /procurement/requisitions/{id}/approval

Process an approval decision (approve, reject, or request revision).

{
  "action":   "approve | reject | revision",
  "comments": "string (required for reject/revision, optional for approve)"
}

Response (200):
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Purchase request approved",
  "data": {
    "requisition": { ...updated requisition... }
  }
}


================================================================================
8. REQUISITION NUMBER AUTO-GENERATION
================================================================================

Generate automatically on create. Must be:
- Unique
- Human-readable
- Include year

Recommended format:  PR-{YEAR}-{SEQUENCE}
Example:             PR-2026-0042

Sequence should be global (not per-department) and zero-padded to 4 digits.
Return `requisition_number` in every response — the frontend displays it prominently.


================================================================================
9. PROJECTS INTEGRATION — DEPENDENCIES
================================================================================

The PR form depends on TWO other endpoints from the Projects module.
Ensure these are working correctly as the PR form calls them on the fly.

--- 9a. Projects List ---

GET /projects?per_page=0

Used to populate the "Project Code" dropdown in the PR header.
Must return all active projects (no pagination when per_page=0).

Each project object must include:
  id, name, project_code

The frontend renders: "{project_code} — {name}" as the option label.
The frontend stores project_code (not id) as the form value.

--- 9b. Project Donors ---

GET /projects/{id}/donors

Used to populate the Donor dropdown after a project is selected.
Called with the project's UUID (not project_code).

Response shape the frontend expects:
{
  "data": {
    "donors": [
      { "id": "uuid", "name": "USAID" },
      { "id": "uuid", "name": "FCDO" }
    ]
  }
}

The frontend stores donor name (not id) as the form value (stored as string on the PR).

--- 9c. Project Budget Lines ---

GET /projects/{id}/budget-lines

THIS IS CRITICAL — this is the new dynamic budget line feature.
Called for each unique project_code in the form (header + all line items).
Called with the project UUID.

Response shape the frontend expects:
{
  "data": {
    "budget_lines": [
      {
        "id":              "uuid",
        "project_id":      "uuid",
        "budget_category": "Training & Capacity Building",
        "description":     "Community Volunteer Training",
        "unit":            "persons",
        "quantity":        50,
        "unit_cost":       15000.00,
        "total_cost":      750000.00
      }
    ]
  }
}

The frontend renders each option as: "{budget_category} — {description}"
The frontend stores `description` as the `budget_line` string value on the line item.

IMPORTANT: The `id`, `budget_category`, and `description` fields are ALL required.
If `data.budget_lines` is missing, the frontend also tries `data` directly as an array.
Prefer always wrapping under `data.budget_lines`.


================================================================================
10. PERMISSIONS — REQUIRED PERMISSION KEYS
================================================================================

Add the following permission keys to the dynamic permissions system.
These must be returned by GET /auth/permissions and managed via settings.

Key                                Description
---                                -----------
procurement.requisitions.view      Can view the purchase requests list
procurement.requisitions.create    Can create a new purchase request
procurement.requisitions.edit      Can edit a PR (only when status is draft/revision)
procurement.requisitions.delete    Can cancel a PR

Suggested defaults:

Role        | view  | create | edit  | delete
------------|-------|--------|-------|-------
super_admin | true  | true   | true  | true   (hardcoded)
admin       | true  | true   | true  | true
manager     | true  | true   | true  | false
staff       | true  | true   | false | false

Note: The approval endpoints should be gated separately (e.g. `procurement.requisitions.approve`).
Add this permission when building the approvals UI.


================================================================================
11. VALIDATION — SERVER-SIDE RULES
================================================================================

Field                  Rule
-----                  ----
title                  required, string, max:255
date                   optional, date format (Y-m-d)
department_id          optional, exists:departments,id
needed_by              optional, date format (Y-m-d)
purchase_scenario      optional, in:Direct Purchase,Competitive Bidding,Framework Agreement,Emergency Purchase,Sole Source
logistics_involved     optional, in:Yes,No
boq                    optional, in:Yes,No
currency               optional, in:NGN,USD,EUR — default: NGN
exchange_rate          required_unless:currency,NGN | numeric | min:0
priority               optional, in:low,medium,high,urgent — default: medium
items                  required on create, array, min 1 item
items.*.description    required, string, max:500
items.*.quantity       optional, numeric, min:0 — default: 1
items.*.estimated_unit_cost  optional, numeric, min:0 — default: 0
items.*.unit           optional, string, max:50
items.*.project_code   optional, string, max:100
items.*.budget_line    optional, string, max:500
items.*.inventory_item_id  optional, uuid, exists:inventory_items,id

Error response shape (422) — matches what the frontend handles:
{
  "success": false,
  "message": "The title field is required.",
  "errors": {
    "title": ["The title field is required."],
    "items.0.description": ["The items.0.description field is required."]
  }
}


================================================================================
12. DELETE / CANCEL BEHAVIOUR
================================================================================

DELETE /procurement/requisitions/{id}

This does NOT hard-delete the record. It sets status = 'cancelled'.
The frontend confirmation dialog says "Cancel Purchase Request" — this is intentional.

Response (200):
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Purchase request cancelled successfully",
  "data": null
}

A hard delete should only be possible for super_admin via a separate admin interface,
not through this endpoint.


================================================================================
13. RESPONSE ENVELOPE — STANDARD FORMAT
================================================================================

Follow the same response envelope used everywhere else in the API:

Success:
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "string",
  "data": { ... }
}

Error (validation):
{
  "success": false,
  "message": "string",
  "errors": { "field": ["message"] }
}

Error (general):
{
  "success": false,
  "message": "string"
}

The frontend's `extractItems(res)` helper tries the following paths in order:
  res.data.requisitions → res.data.items → res.data.data → res.data → res

Use `data.requisitions` for the list endpoint.
Use `data.requisition` for single-item endpoints (create, get, update, submit, approval).


